{{\pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\adjustright \b\f1\fs28\kerning28\cgrid 
Introduction
\par}
{\tc\tcl2 \v Introduction}
The {\field {\*\fldinst { HYPERLINK  \\l "AAAAAAAACL" }{}}{\fldrslt {\cs37\ul\cf2 Balancer}}} is a self-balancing two-wheel robot built on an STM32F4 microcontroller. Before this project, the codebase already provided a working pitch (tilt) controller \'96 the robot could hold the upright position and follow manually defined turn routines \'96 together with a set of OOP-style C drivers ({\f2 {\field {\*\fldinst { HYPERLINK  \\l "AAAAAAAACN" }{}}{\fldrslt {\cs37\ul\cf2 MPU6050_t}}}} , {\f2 {\field {\*\fldinst { HYPERLINK  \\l "AAAAAAAACP" }{}}{\fldrslt {\cs37\ul\cf2 TOFSensor_t}}}} , {\f2 {\field {\*\fldinst { HYPERLINK  \\l "AAAAAAAACR" }{}}{\fldrslt {\cs37\ul\cf2 Stepper_t}}}} , {\f2 {\field {\*\fldinst { HYPERLINK  \\l "AAAAAAAACV" }{}}{\fldrslt {\cs37\ul\cf2 PIDContr_t}}}} , {\f2 {\field {\*\fldinst { HYPERLINK  \\l "AAAAAAAACZ" }{}}{\fldrslt {\cs37\ul\cf2 MeanVal_t}}}} , {\f2 {\field {\*\fldinst { HYPERLINK  \\l "AAAAAAAAAN" }{}}{\fldrslt {\cs37\ul\cf2 analogCh_t}}}} ).\par
This contribution to the project is split into two coupled parts:\par
{
\par
\pard\plain \s140\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\fs20\cgrid 
1.\tab {\b Refactoring.}  The top-level program (old {\f2 {\field {\*\fldinst { HYPERLINK  \\l "AAAAAAAASJ" }{}}{\fldrslt {\cs37\ul\cf2 main.c}}}} ) is reorganised into an OOP-inspired {\f2 {\field {\*\fldinst { HYPERLINK  \\l "AAAAAAAACM" }{}}{\fldrslt {\cs37\ul\cf2 Balancer_t}}}}  that owns all sensors, actuators, controllers and state. The new {\f2 {\field {\*\fldinst { HYPERLINK  \\l "AAAAAAAASJ" }{}}{\fldrslt {\cs37\ul\cf2 main.c}}}}  is reduced to hardware instantiation, peripheral init, and a thin scheduler that calls the object's methods.\par
\pard\plain \s140\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\fs20\cgrid 
2.\tab {\b Cascaded distance control.}  A new task mode {\f2 {\field {\*\fldinst { HYPERLINK  \\l "AAAAAAAABJ" }{}}{\fldrslt {\cs37\ul\cf2 M_DistCtrl}}}}  is added. An outer distance loop (TOF sensor \u8594? target velocity) and a middle velocity loop (wheel-derived velocity \u8594? target acceleration \u8594? pitch offset) are wrapped around the existing inner pitch loop. The robot is meant to demonstrate the {\i distance control} -function on a treadmill.\par}
\par
Function- and field-level documentation is placed directly as Doxygen comments in the source files. This page introduces the two parts and the diagrams that explain the architecture.\par
